<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What hydration should I use for pizza dough?", answer: "For a home oven, 60-65% hydration produces a manageable dough that bakes well at 500-550 degrees F. Neapolitan-style pizza uses 58-65% hydration. New York style works at 62-65%. Higher hydration (70%+) creates a lighter, more airy crust but is harder to handle." },
  { question: "How much dough do I need per pizza?", answer: "A 10-inch pizza needs about 200g of dough, a 12-inch needs 250g, a 14-inch needs 300g, and a 16-inch needs 350g. These weights produce a thin to medium-thickness crust." },
  { question: "Should I cold ferment pizza dough?", answer: "Cold fermentation (24-72 hours in the fridge) develops significantly more flavor and improves the dough's texture and extensibility. Use less yeast (0.1-0.3% of flour weight) for cold ferments. The dough can be used after 24 hours and improves up to 48-72 hours." },
  { question: "What type of yeast should I use?", answer: "Instant dry yeast (IDY) is the most convenient; it can be mixed directly into flour without proofing. Active dry yeast (ADY) should be dissolved in warm water first. Fresh yeast uses roughly 3x the amount of instant yeast by weight." },
  { question: "Why does my pizza dough shrink back when stretching?", answer: "The gluten is too tight. Let the dough rest at room temperature for at least 1-2 hours after removing from the fridge. If it still springs back, cover it and wait another 15-30 minutes. Proper fermentation and relaxation are key to extensible dough." }
]) %>

